        "teacherMoves": "Project each slide for 40 seconds, then advance. Say: 'You collected all of this evidence over twelve lessons. Today, all of it comes together.' After the parade, ask: 'Which single piece of evidence do you think is most important for explaining why the Huruma kettle was slow? Write your answer — do not shout it out.' [WAIT TIME: 15 seconds.] Cold-call 4 students with different answers to create productive disagreement: 'Korir says the internal resistance graph. Fatuma says the series-circuit ammeter data. Let's hold that tension — your final explanation will tell us who is right, or whether both matter.' This primes students for the synthesis they will do in Phase 3.",
